      <scopecontent id="aspace_2d3a92e7c99916dc9c520bf8691780c2">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Samuel Wood Papers date 1849-1920 and are principally concerned with the Wood family of Greytown, Nicaragua, and the bombardment of Greytown by the American ship <emph render="italic">Cyane</emph> in 1854.</p>
         <p>The rush across Central America by Forty-Niners bound for California resulted in a backwash of Americans who remained there to engage in trade. Those gathered at San Juan del Norte, or Greytown, organized themselves into an independent free-trade city. Among the prominent merchants of this place was Samuel Smith Wood who carried on an extensive and lucrative business. Among the more substantial citizens, Wood possessed a large and valuable stock of merchandise and was the owner of a number of buildings at Greytown.</p>
         <p>In 1854, a dispute broke out between some of the residents of Greytown and the American minister there, and the United States government dispatched the ship <emph render="italic">Cyane</emph> to investigate. An account of what followed is given in a lengthly letter written by Alexander McCready Wood, son of Samuel Smith Wood, dated 1854 July 15. He writes: "The <emph render="italic">Cyane</emph> arrived here on Tuesday night last and on Wednesday morning Captain Hollis notified the inhabitants of our town that indemnification to the amount of $28,000 was demanded by his government and unless the terms were complied with by eight o'clock on Thursday morning, he would blow and bombard the town to atoms which the inhabitants failing to do, his threat was actually and faithfully carried into effect and our once pleasant little town lies in a heap of smouldering ruins."</p>
         <p>Captain Hollis' act, which was generally condemned, gave rise to numerous actions against the American government. The Wood family presented a memorial to Congress asking indemnity for their large losses. Many of the papers are concerned with this case.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_2c536dd4a1b7010c77d7390a98475d73">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Samuel Smith Wood worked in flour manufacturing in New York City until ca. 1826. He moved to a farm in Coutlandville, where he remained until 1834. Wood then went to California prospecting for gold. In 1852 he established a trading post at San Juan del Norte (Greytown), Nicaragua.</p>  
      </bioghist>
  
